<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE153692E9E1F" blockId="2.[166,1225,1567,1850]" box="[219,1111,1567,1594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3C34E16C6FC69E1C" box="[628,703,1567,1593]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1719,1741]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1233,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig.7–12. Eggs of Erebidae:Hermeniinae:7, 8 — Pechipogo strigilata; Hypeninae:9–11 — Hypena proboscidalis; Phytometrinae: 12 — Colobochyla salicalis. Scale bars: 7–11 — 10 µm; 12 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3C8AE16C6F919E1F" box="[714,744,1567,1594]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">13</figureCitation>
), diameter 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD6C80F3D2EE16C6E809E1F" box="[878,1017,1567,1594]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.499999999999999" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" unit="mm" value="0.6499999999999999" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.7 mm</quantity>
(n = 2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD6C8093E9BE14C6EE99F0E" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="557" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE14C6C899EDC" blockId="2.[166,1225,1567,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surface. Micropylar area represented by rosette and 3 rows short and wide petalled cells. Rosette with 5 petalled cells and 5 micropylar openings (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3F62E10C6C089EBF" box="[290,369,1663,1690]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 14</figureCitation>
). There are 15–16 of the 44–47 zig-zag longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of micropylar area. Transverse walls less distinct and narrow than ridges. Aeropyles large, bordered by roller-like edges, diameter of which greater than width of ribs (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3A2EE1CC69C29EFF" box="[1134,1211,1727,1754]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Chorion folded everywhere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE18C6EF19F1C" blockId="2.[166,1225,1567,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">S h a p e o f g n a w e d h o l e s i n e g g s. Caterpillar nibbles out large oval opening at the lateral part of egg, sometimes opening being made apically.</paragraph>
